    <br>
    <p>The three main parts of the Transit:</p>
    <div class="container-fluid">
        <h3>Alidade (Upper Plate):</h3>
        <ul class="list-group list-group-flush">
            <li class="list-group-item"><b>Telescope</b> – The main sighting component used to view and align with
                distant targets; mounted on the transit for angular measurements.</li>
            <li class="list-group-item"><b>Standards</b> – Either the A- or U-standard, refers to the two upright
                supports on an engineer's transit that hold the telescope and its horizontal axis.</li>
            <li class="list-group-item"><b>Compass Box</b> – Contains a magnetic compass used for determining
                approximate bearings or orientation, with respect to the magnetic meridian, during field setup.</li>
            <li class="list-group-item"><b>Plate Level Vials</b> – Bubble levels mounted on the base plate to ensure the
                instrument is leveled horizontally before taking angular measurements.</li>
            <li class="list-group-item"><b>Vertical Circle</b> – A graduated circular scale attached to the telescope,
                used for measuring vertical angles or elevation differences.</li>
            <li class="list-group-item"><b>Plate Verniers</b> – Small, precise scales used to read minute divisions on
                the horizontal and vertical circles, enhancing angular accuracy.</li>
            <li class="list-group-item"><b>Optical Plummet</b> – A built-in optical device that helps center the
                instrument precisely over a ground point or survey station.</li>
            <li class="list-group-item"><b>Telescope Clamp</b> – Locks the telescope in position after sighting a
                target, preventing unwanted vertical angle movement during angle reading.</li>
            <li class="list-group-item"><b>Telescope Tangent Screw</b> – A fine adjustment screw that allows precise
                vertical angle movement of the telescope for accurate target alignment.</li>
            <li class="list-group-item"><b>Upper Clamp</b> – Secures the upper part of the instrument (usually the
                alidade) to the base, locking horizontal rotation.</li>
            <li class="list-group-item"><b>Upper Tangent Screw</b> – Provides fine horizontal adjustment of the
                instrument after clamping, used for precise horizontal angle setting.</li>
        </ul>
    </div>
